  "tips": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "topic": "padac_with_precipitation",
      "content": "The verb 'padać' is commonly used with weather nouns like rain, snow, and hail.",
      "examples": [
        "Rano padał deszcz. = It rained in the morning.",
        "Często pada tu grad. = It often hails here.",
        "Kiedy ostatnio padał śnieg? = When was the last time it snowed?"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "topic": "spoken_weather_short_forms",
      "content": "When it's raining, you can say 'pada deszcz'. In spoken, informal Polish you can also shorten it to just 'pada'. You can also use 'leje' when it's pouring.",
      "examples": [
        "Pada deszcz.",
        "Pada.",
        "Leje."
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "topic": "single_present_tense_weather",
      "content": "Polish has only one present tense, so depending on context, 'pada deszcz' can be understood as 'it's raining' or 'it rains'."
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "topic": "heavy_rain_light_rain",
      "content": "Useful weather expressions to memorise:",
      "examples": [
        "ulewny deszcz = heavy rain",
        "lekki deszcz = light rain",
        "Mocno pada. = It's raining heavily."
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 11,
      "topic": "temperature_question_alternative",
      "content": "You can also ask about temperature with 'Ile jest dziś stopni?', which has the same meaning as 'Jaka jest dziś temperatura?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 12,
      "topic": "stopien_number_forms",
      "content": "The noun 'stopień' (degree) changes depending on the number that precedes it.",
      "examples": [
        "1 stopień",
        "2, 3, 4 stopnie",
        "5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10 stopni",
        "22 stopnie",
        "15 stopni",
        "113 stopni",
        "4 stopnie",
        "1 stopień"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 13,
      "topic": "cien_and_w_cieniu",
      "content": "'Cień' means shade or shadow. 'W cieniu' means 'in the shade'."
    },
    {
      "id": 14,
      "topic": "celsjusza_in_spoken_polish",
      "content": "In spoken Polish, it's not very common to explicitly say 'Celsjusza' when talking about temperature. You're more likely to hear it in forecasts."
    },
    {
      "id": 16,
      "topic": "trzeba_impersonal",
      "content": "'Trzeba' is a very useful impersonal word. It is a less formal way to say something is necessary or needs to be done.",
      "examples": [
        "Trzeba jechać metrem. = You need to take the underground.",
        "Trzeba iść do sklepu. = You need to go to the shop."
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 20,
      "topic": "compass_points_with_na",
      "content": "Use these phrases to talk about compass directions:",
      "examples": [
        "na północy = in the north",
        "na południu = in the south",
        "na zachodzie = in the west",
        "na wschodzie = in the east"
      ],
      "content_note": "With compass points, Polish uses the preposition 'na', not 'w'."
    },
    {
      "id": 24,
      "topic": "wieje_wiatr",
      "content": "A common phrase is 'wieje wiatr' = 'the wind is blowing'."
    },
    {
      "id": 27,
      "topic": "duzo_tutaj_pada_not_duzo_pada_deszcz",
      "content": "The book notes that the form 'Dużo tutaj/tu pada' sounds more natural than a more literal construction with 'deszcz'."
    },
    {
      "id": 29,
      "topic": "weather_describing_adjectives",
      "content": "Useful adjectives for describing weather:",
      "examples": [
        "piękna = beautiful",
        "ładna = nice",
        "brzydka = ugly / bad",
        "okropna = terrible",
        "zmienna = changeable"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 30,
      "topic": "wysoka_niska_temperatura",
      "content": "The feminine adjectives 'wysoka' and 'niska' describe temperature here. In other contexts, they can mean tall and short / high and low."
    },
    {
      "id": 34,
      "topic": "w_koncu_vs_na_koncu",
      "content": "Do not confuse 'w końcu' with 'na końcu'. 'W końcu' means finally / in the end. 'Na końcu' means at the end.",
      "examples": [
        "W końcu to zrobiłeś! = You finally did it!",
        "Mój dom jest na końcu ulicy. = My house is at the end of the street."
      ]
    }
  ],
